TY  - JOUR
AU  - Subrahmanyam, Marti G.
AU  - Tang, Dragon Yongjun
AU  - Wang, Sarah Qian
T1  - Does the Tail Wag the Dog?: The Effect of Credit Default Swaps on Credit Risk
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhu038
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 10
SP  - 2927
EP  - 2960
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We use credit default swaps (CDS) trading data to demonstrate that the credit risk of reference firms, reflected in rating downgrades and bankruptcies, increases significantly upon the inception of CDS trading, a finding that is robust after controlling for the endogeneity of CDS trading. Additionally, distressed firms are more likely to file for bankruptcy if they are linked to CDS trading. Furthermore, firms with more “no restructuring” contracts than other types of CDS contracts (i.e., contracts that include restructuring) are more adversely affected by CDS trading, and the number of creditors increases after CDS trading begins, exacerbating creditor coordination failure in the resolution of financial distress.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhu038
ER  - 



